data.content:
Your test works but has weak assertions — `Assert.IsTrue` gives unhelpful failure messages like "Expected: True, Actual: False". MSTest has dedicated collection assertions:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Use AreEqual for exact count — shows expected vs actual on failure
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Use CollectionAssert for collection-specific checks
    CollectionAssert.AllAreSatisfied(users, u => Assert.IsTrue(u.IsActive));

    // Use Assert.IsNotNull + AreEqual instead of Assert.IsTrue(x != null)
    var admin = users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreNotEqual(0, list.Count)` or just check exact count | Shows actual value on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(count == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, count)` | Message: *"Expected:3 Actual:5"* vs *"Expected:True Actual:False"* |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(x)` | Clearer intent and message |

**Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods:**
- `CollectionAssert.Contains(list, item)` — item exists
- `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` — same items, any order
- `CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` — same items, same order
- `CollectionAssert.AllAreSatisfied(list, action)` — every element passes *(MSTest v3+)*

The general rule: **avoid `Assert.IsTrue` for anything that has a dedicated assertion** — you get much better diagnostics on failure.
